unding the analysis in a broader historical context, Browning finds that nation branding is politically significant, though not necessarily for the reasons its advocates claim. Specifically, the book raises important questions about nation branding’s influence on the constitution of national identity, the reframing of citizenship, and the topography of contemporary geopolitics.Nation Branding and International Politics considers how status, prestige, and reputation are constructed and maintained in international society, and how, perhaps, this construction and maintenance may be changing – just as the practice of nation branding is changing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBranding (Marketing)xPolitical aspects. 0aNational characteristicsxPolitical aspects. 0aWorld politics. 70(DE-588)4065835-10(DE-627)1061168190(DE-576)209161051aWettbewerb2gnd 70(DE-588)4072885-70(DE-627)1060939320(DE-576)209188553aInternationale Politik2gnd 70(DE-588)4125488-00(DE-627)1057398550(DE-576)209576979aInternationales politisches System2gnd 70(DE-588)4134262-80(DE-627)1056739510(DE-576)209650796aPolitische Kommunikation2gnd 70(DE-588)4175418-90(DE-627)1053644520(DE-576)209963441aPosition2gnd 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Communication Policy.2bisacsh  aColombia.  aCountry.  aNordic.  aNorth Korea.  aRussia.  aSimon Anholt.  aSouth Africa.  aThailand.  acorporate.  ademocracy.  agoodism.  aontological.  apolicy.  apower.  asubaltern.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228019459?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228019459423Coveruh